This paper is likely to belong to the arXiv CS sub-category of Speech and Dialogue Processing (cs.SD) as it focuses on discovering speech features and acoustic tokens directly from unlabeled speech data. It also mentions the Zero Resource Speech Challenge organized at Interspeech 2015, which is a well-known challenge in the speech and dialogue processing community. 

It could also belong to the sub-category of Computation and Language (cs.CL) as it involves natural language processing and the discovery of acoustic tokens that carry different characteristics for the given corpus and language. 

The paper also involves deep learning techniques, which could place it in the sub-categories of Machine Learning (cs.LG), Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI), and Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE).
